# BunGo (Bundler 4 Go) - Framework Rules and Context

## 1. Project Motivation & Philosophy
BunGo is a lightweight, high-performance idiomatic Go web framework and asset bundler. It allows developers to write Go server logic and React (JSX) views in the same repository, seamlessly binding them together without Node.js, npm, or complex external build pipelines.

## 2. AI Agent Directive (CRITICAL)
**All AI agents working on this project MUST continuously keep this `.cursorrules` file updated with the most up-to-date, comprehensive understanding of the framework's architecture, conventions, and guidelines. If you introduce a structural change, a new standard, or modify a core behaviour, you must update this file immediately to reflect it.**

**In addition to updating `.cursorrules`, ALL AI agents MUST continuously keep the `README.md` file up to date with the most recent usage patterns, features, and examples to serve as an accurate, comprehensive guide for developers using this framework.**

**Whenever changes are made to how the library works or its features, AI agents MUST also automatically update the relevant documentation files inside the `docs/` directory. This is critical for preserving developer documentation structures.**

## 3. Core Architectural Boundaries (CRITICAL)
* **Embedded Bundling & React:** BunGo embeds `esbuild` directly via its Go API (`github.com/evanw/esbuild/pkg/api`). Furthermore, BunGo **embeds React and React-DOM directly into the Go binary** using `//go:embed` inside `internal/builder/vendor/`. An esbuild plugin (in `internal/builder/react_plugin.go`) intercepts `import "react"`, `import "react-dom"` / `react-dom/client`, and `import "bungo/render"`. The virtual module `bungo/render` exports `_bungoRender(Component, elementId?)` and `useBungoData()` so views can mount their root component and read page handler data without importing helpers from `react-dom/client` or touching `window.__BUNGO_DATA__` directly; when `elementId` is omitted it defaults to `"root"`. BunGo supports local view entry files in `.jsx`, `.tsx`, `.js`, and `.ts`. BunGo also supports Deno-style remote URL imports in JSX/TSX (for example `https://esm.sh/...`) through `internal/builder/remote_import_plugin.go`, which resolves and fetches remote ESM modules (including relative imports between remote modules) at build time. Remote modules that reference React/ReactDOM URL variants are normalized back to BunGo's embedded React runtime to prevent duplicate React instances and hook/context crashes. The React JSX automatic runtime shim preserves `key` semantics (third `jsx` argument), so keyed lists reconcile correctly and keys are not rendered as child text. The compiler uses esbuild's `Inject: ["bungo/render"]` so `_bungoRender` / `useBungoData` are auto-injected and view files do not need to import them.
* **Theme / locale:** User-facing CLI strings, dev TUI copy, and scaffold error messages default to English in `internal/theme/en.go` (`theme.EN`). Shared version constants (`EmbeddedReactVersion`, `ScaffoldGoVersion`, `CLIVersionUnknown`) live in `internal/theme/versions.go`. The root package re-exports `EmbeddedReactVersion` for API stability.
* **CLI (`cmd/bungo`) & Dev Mode:** BunGo ships a Cobra-based helper command at `cmd/bungo`. `bungo init <project-name>` scaffolds a runnable showcase project (Go server, routes, templates, and React view) and includes remote `https://...` import usage in the generated view to demonstrate full embedded bundling functionality. Passing `--typescript` generates a `.tsx` showcase view and `tsconfig.json`. `bungo dev` (CLI in `cmd/bungo`, implementation in `internal/dev`) runs `go run <entry>` from project root (`--entry`, default `"."`), starts a websocket endpoint at `/__bungo` on fixed port 35729 (`bungo.DevWebSocketPort`), uses `fsnotify` (recursive dir watches with ignore rules) to detect source/template/view changes, debounces burst events before reload, disconnects websocket clients, restarts the app process, and enables browser auto-refresh on reconnect. The framework detects dev mode via `BUNGO_DEV_ENABLED=1` and injects a small reconnect client script (same port) into rendered pages.
* **No Node.js / NPM:** Never generate `package.json`, `node_modules`, or npm commands.
* **No Business Logic:** The framework is strictly infrastructure. It routes requests, applies security layers, compiles JSX, and renders templates. It must NEVER import database drivers or user-specific models.
* **Fail-Fast Asset Validation:** The server strictly requires the provided `webDir` and its `layouts/` and `views/` subdirectories to exist at boot. It will immediately `panic()` if they are missing or if a registered page requests a missing template/layout/view file. If a Layout (per-route or `DefaultLayout`) is specified, that layout file must exist.
* **Template vs Layout:** `Template` is always required—the page-specific `.gohtml` file in `layouts/`. `Layout` is optional and enables Go template composition: a wrapper template (e.g., `base.gohtml`) defines `{{block "content" .}}`; the Template fills it with `{{define "content"}}...{{end}}`, avoiding repeated `<html><head><body>` boilerplate. `Server.DefaultLayout` sets a global layout for all pages that do not specify their own.
* **Automated Template Injection:** `RenderTemplate` injects `window.__BUNGO_DATA__` and the compiled JSX bundle automatically. When no Layout is used: scripts go before `</head>` or `</body>`. When a Layout is used: scripts are injected into the layout. Developers must NOT manually place these script tags in their views.
* **Agnostic Handlers & Rendering:** 
  - Page Handler signature: `func(req *bungo.Request) (map[string]any, error)`
  - API Handler signature: `func(req *bungo.Request) (bungo.APIResponse, error)`
  - The internal `RenderTemplate` returns formatted HTML entirely agnostic of the Server environment. Adapters (e.g., `HTTPEngine`) are responsible for passing this to an `http.ResponseWriter` or corresponding vendor boundary.
* **Configuration Structs:** Use pass-by-value for configuration structs (e.g., `PageRoute`, `ApiRoute`, `SecurityLayer`) during server initialization.

## 4. Core Terminology
* **`Server`**: The central registry. Holds routing maps, security layers, and delegates listening to the `Engine`.
* **`Engine`**: An interface (`Invoker`) representing the execution environment. Translates incoming events (e.g., standard `net/http` or AWS Lambda) into a generic `bungo.Request`. Available engines: `engine.NewHTTPEngine()` (net/http), `engine_aws.NewLambdaEngine()` (AWS Lambda HTTP API v2 / Function URL), `engine_gcp.NewGCPEngine(name)` (Google Cloud Functions).
* **`Request`**: Framework-agnostic HTTP request representation containing Headers, GET/POST Params, Body (raw bytes or parsed interface), and an `Internal` map for passing context (like JWT claims) between Security Layers and Handlers.
* **`APIResponse`**: Contains an HTTP `StatusCode` (int) and a `Body` (any) to be marshaled to JSON.
* **`Template`**: The required page-specific `.gohtml` file in `layouts/`. Defines page content, optionally with `{{define "content"}}` when using Layout composition.
* **`Layout`**: Optional wrapper template in `layouts/` that defines `{{block "content" .}}`. Used for composition to avoid repeating `<html><head><body>` in every template.